   <abstract >The threat of anthropogenic climate change on extreme weather events such as extreme heat and cold warrants an investigation to improve how extreme weather is identified and forecasted. The Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) defines an extreme temperature event based on a certain temperature threshold or as an event that is below or above the 10th or 90th percentile of a probability distribution, respectively. The problem with this approach is the IPCC uses two meter surface temperature data that contains high and low frequencies embedded. These frequencies contain non-stationary properties that make it difficult to determine how extreme temperatures are changing due to the concept of a moving mean. This thesis proposes a timescale decomposition that extracts the higher frequencies and leaves out the non-stationary influence. By focusing on the probability distribution functions (PDF) of the higher frequencies, statistical moments, such as standard deviation, skewness, and kurtosis, can be used to spatially and temporally locate extreme temperatures. While other data analysis methods exist, most of them either do not apply to non-stationary data or are not as simple as the decomposition scheme used in this project. The timescale decomposition method is very effective in providing piecewise moment plots and global contour figures depicting the moment values and how they changed with time. A specific grid point, region, or globe can be analyzed through decadal intervals to fully observe trends in the moments and can even be used to detect atmospheric patterns. The procedure also revealed a multi-decadal rate of change in the moments which is left unexplained and for future researchers to investigate.</abstract>
